{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84d6757c-e367-432c-afc5-eb59958d42a1","content":"TUnit uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** natively, so it uses `--treenode-filter` (not VSTest `--filter`). The treenode path format is `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThis matches the `SmsNotificationTests` class in any assembly/namespace and runs all its tests (`SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"937125d6-f158-4c58-ace1-39cbeb05341d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively, not VSTest. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, to filter by class name, you use `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nOr with `dotnet test`, TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP. The filter syntax for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter`.\n\nActually, let me think about this. TUnit projects set `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` which means they use MTP natively. \n\nWith `dotnet test` and MTP, you can pass the treenode filter through the `--` separator, so the syntax would be `dotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"` to filter by the test class name.\n\nThe treenode filter format follows the pattern `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`, so `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*` matches any test in that class. However, I need to clarify whether `dotnet test --filter` actually translates to `--treenode-filter` for MTP-based runners like TUnit, or if you need to use the `--` separator to pass the filter directly to the MTP runner.","outputTokens":756,"requestId":"3402:15E90A:AF79ED:CD75A3:69F40217"},"id":"dc1ab670-34f8-4ab7-87da-b5aeb7a71ee9","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:15.727Z","parentId":"436fd685-d10b-4fdc-81d2-6369e64af959"}
